The Parliament did not ratify the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, in the context of an amendment to the criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph concerning the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected on second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing the penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must rule on the sentenced woman's appeal in December.
Tymosenko qualifies the regime's political revenge judgment and has provoked a process of suspicion of court bias also to the west.
The draft to annul paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
