History of IBM: From slices of cheese to flights in the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was renamed IBM in 1924 - originally a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 chaired the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the firm’s founder – Watson’s ideas have been the foundation of the company’s identity and culture to date.
Watson ran the firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenue multiplied to $9 million and the firm began expanding to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of leadership it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos – on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight to the Moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name of IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the Consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM for the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited such as transport and city management.
As for the field of commerce IBM has recently developed a platform "Smarter Commerce" that helps salespeople manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our territory.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that deals with speech recognition.
