How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a penchant for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually for example to Poland or the Soviet Union he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West however you had to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not won yet.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, the Czechs’ travels have undergone a great revolution.
Although up until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak,Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holiday days in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in western neighbouring countries led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take with you your own food canned, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech krona which allowed our tourists to finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased which has caused around 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with connections by air charters that through contracts have greatly reduced the costs compared to what there was before.
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most of the developed countries around the world apart from the U.S. which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully rank in the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time again in history they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for holidays abroad including ancillary charges.
