21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion That Moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with highs, lows and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruins.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about a modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, glass sheds, bold and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the famous world exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight, suspended steel and glass construction.
Construction is considered to this day as an important milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian Universal Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it eventually became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the Universal Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the South Railway Station in Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suited for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However it was also used for a long time, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has become increasingly decaying.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st Century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a lucky shot in every respect.
The new start was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she particularly carried out the work of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments.
Except for contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookstore are located there, and an office must be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of its move to Vienna and by its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a gulf of energy," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was placed and the roof replaced by a special safety glass.
The thermal bridge beams have been reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a light panel sifted between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - this is almost a new construction, but still the lightweight Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in a red-brown rust protection shade.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for the monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also pleases the monuments protection office," says Krischanitz and draws attention to a rough basement floor.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz said recently, a typical "Drop-in-the-City" story.
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a stroke of luck of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the newly planned "quartier of the central station", with offices and apartments.
And maybe another lucky blow will happen: the 21st century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
