Peter Englund's new book, "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War," opens with a long list of heart-wrenching characters.
A tip to get started: carefully tear this page apart and make it your bookmark.
In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book that he describes, with accuracy, as "an anti-history work."
It has a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; almost no ambassadors or discussion of strategies and materials are found.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like," including "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods."
“Beauty and Sorrow” sums up the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance workers, and vendors.
Some of them will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war, some will lose members, go crazy, or lose their lives.
Their lives falter here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
He refutes the idea that World War I was summed up only in the terrible trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skilfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tse-tse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is touching from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you're a mother at home, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but they are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them deal with deprivation and the ability to get away with it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, überall ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He's prosecuting on replacement food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed into sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made from dried roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
