Easy... Log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to find them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently published by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is littered with so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have done it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. They targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to a survey. The questions asked were about their level of education, their attitudes towards their own future violence and their optimism.
By getting in touch with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screen.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Focus groups, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study all topics that touch on health issues such as social trends, through Likes, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three pieces of content a day, the “data supernova” is generating a search explosion, increasing the number of search jobs whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you might not approach on the street.
“Before, when you tried to conduct investigations into people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you in,” says Jamie Bartlett.
“Facebook avoids all of this – you have direct access to their information.”
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues, young students who talked on Facebook about their drunken exploits were much more likely to be alcoholics than students who were discreet about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that student colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you don't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle-based Children's Research Institute, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise be unrecognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics regarding the love situation and Valentine's Day, the turnout rate in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available - digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its treasure trove of data available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, there is something else online.
“I don’t think a large number of users have ever thought about the fact that a researcher can study their profile,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London’s Knowledge Laboratory, based on a 2006 study he conducted by observing his students’ Facebook walls.
"As far as they knew, the exchanges were seen only by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on the wall of a user.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things,” says Neil Selwyn.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and pen remain the best tools one can use.
