7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, at the Movies This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some have compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will air this week in the first part of a film on major markets, is how much this creative mind had understood the processes and workflows of products.
He was no doubt a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart improver - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease that made them think that a great idea did 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work produced an exception to the idea."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years since Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aiming for a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in the transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full-length video was found in the director’s garage.
This video, slightly edited, is the basis of the 68-minute film called Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will air in theaters next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide an accurate answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbows to make him speed up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, we find a strangely present aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision on the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous reviews of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable Lost Interview sequences:
On how he learned to run a business:
“During all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers are constantly the same, ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to give details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" evaluated by nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a trick on the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack phone networks and phone free long-distance.
The device has been the subject of many prior writings, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public telephone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We would wrap the ball of different things half a dozen times and you would scream on the pay phone and it would happen to you a minute later on the pay phone next door,” Jobs said.
“We were young and through this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn't know much, but we invented a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by recounting a wonderful trick he and Wozniak devised: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go insanely laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
About his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s approach):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looks for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and makes a call to him.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP's employees to visit the company's research laboratories, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode-ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
In several moments in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a whim.
Early in his career, as he settled down to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working with only 30 days of credit, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished appliances.
Later, at Apple, he recalled the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some big fights... they were yelling at me that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300] and I had enough, I went out and went to a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and it turned out to be incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are running out of steam:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Suppose you worked at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success.
Sales and marketing can evolve it, so [it’s these types of people] who end up leading companies and product staff are sidelined from decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this position of monopoly is completely rotten by people who can’t imagine designing a good product versus a bad product – the manual labor required.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They snatched defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to be made...Some things you can’t do, the electrons can, the glass, the robots, the factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It's about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed of stealing great ideas.
This is partly what makes the Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
