How to Spot a Lie
A look at recent headlines indicates just how ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, has passed for an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who lived through the story will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at the school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers gave test responses to students in order to be seen on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to exclaim, "I had you," deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research into such projects, notably in psychology and physiology.
One of the findings of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They do not stutter, blush or always stir.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A skilled lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial microexpressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and still emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are skilled at reading others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies “centered on themselves” while women tell more lies “centered on others” – usually to protect someone’s feelings – that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "setting the benchmark data".
This helps provide a reference point to measure future changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves their feet permanently so as not to make unfair accusations when you see them moving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of verbal and non-verbal misleading behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, lean toward an exit, change posture significantly, or present “post-interview” relief – an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change in posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
Famous Scott Peterson slipped using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distant language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Ms. Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... if I remember correctly... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
