Climate adversity has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's management, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in return there is a deterioration of the main development indicators.
The low temperatures in February, apart from causing trillion-dollar losses for the agricultural sector, limited the state's economic opportunities for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historical decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the frost allocation report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage to 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity has generated, up to November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of unemployment of the state during the first three quarters of the year has been observed an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent for the second quarter of the year and 5 per cent for the second quarter.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we’re seeing is a rise in unemployment that’s due to a variety of factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a resource constraint by legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who make dollars illegally it’s not easy for them to work for them, to invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because on entering they already have a lot of difficulties to find work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloa labour market worsens considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for the lag for the state are the low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the FDI of the State reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the previous year of the same period.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July at the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos, destined for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State congress was no 2.600 trillion pesos.
Reactions
For the representatives of the employers’ sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés’ government demonstrates a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
"The performance of the economy of Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we must work intensively to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we must double our effort, we had to align the effort of all and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year have constrained the state's economy and restricted its yield and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, among which the frosts, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the Vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana de Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and the economic direction of the state, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he says.
Lots to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there is some progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in how public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do," he said.
