The Court validates the "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and House of Representatives have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called “analog cut” from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to concretize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, due to the fact that the regulation of radio and television is an attribution reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favor of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions foreseen by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of ministers resolved to dismiss the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the presiding minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the bill, in that the federal executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also do not consider that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has the constitutional mandate of the state leadership.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this translates into better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the change, he argued, would be postponing the benefits of digitization that involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompasses a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that many countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded in a form the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assured.
The possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán is being analyzed
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 to 6 thousand to 74 trials.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local norms with federal electoral reform.
It will be remembered that Michoacán did not homologate either its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Act, at the same time as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral process to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for by the Journal of Electoral Justice.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called the state proxy’s vote for constitutional reforms “invalid and illegal” because he has no right to “sanction or challenge” them.
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out the partial and total counts of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of the ballot and counting in the ballot file is not with the president of the ballot; or there are errors or obvious alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total number of votes received in all polls of the election may be counted when there is an indication that the difference between the supposed winner of the respective election and the one who obtained second place in the poll is equal to or below one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or coalition.
The total count of the ballot can also be made if at the end of the common count it turns out that the difference between the supposed winner and the second-place candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate came out second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16%, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
