There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge relevant despite the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the bands that came up at the same time and, if that’s relevant now, I think it’s wonderful because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting, because I think there are songs on the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that qualify as very obscure songs, even though these may sound a bit positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply dark songs.
I think if you grow up and there’s trauma in your life and you lose a relative or friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
I also think you can be happy and even make dark music like that.
