Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the takeoff of the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"Evidence that the unit has had various contacts with the ground, the blades have had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit has lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the impact zone do not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In research it has been reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact presented itself in a structural way.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For now, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, General Manager of Airports and Auxiliary Services assured that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was operating at cruise speed and this happened on soft ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, TBS holder Pérez Jácome listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed according to the visual flight rules, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-lying cloud layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought a lower altitude area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last radar recording of the aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The aircraft debris dispersion model suggests that the helicopter collided with the ground under structural integrity conditions.
No traces of fire or explosion were detected:
In the place of the loss there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above average sea level, with a gradient of seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disarticulated himself along his journey.
The information provides evidence that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful search in a larger area than the encircled area around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, supporting the presumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and youth; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the "Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents" protocol that will have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the population with or without entitlement to participate, to present themselves at the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the proofs to the minors are carried out every Saturday from 8:00 hours.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 miners, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to diet.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family heredity history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic (people associated with childhood obesity are being identified) will be applied to all participants on Saturdays.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there has been a 77 percent increase in obesity for boys and 47 percent for girls; there has also been a dramatic increase in overweight," he said.
He said the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American, 30 percent European and five percent African heredity and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy one consumes (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they are overweight or obese.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential way, doctors give it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryness, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - cornmeal batter wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
The asphalt of the UNAM would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 blackcurrants each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the tar pavement is completely eliminated, even blackcurrants could be reduced.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The CF researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass by generating stress, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the layer of asphalt, he says, a last layer called a rolling layer is put, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes blackheads.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that spoils is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be cured at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrant and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
