Japan revived after the earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy was paralyzed, still recovering after the devastating earthquake that became the nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the country since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Government of Tokyo estimated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to turn the page definitively: the GDP rose by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - is also the fastest pace of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refuge values" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the turmoil forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floatline is determined by the health of major technology groups.
