Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, according to Royal Society of Canada report
On palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to deliver better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of a large report by the Royal Society of Canada, involving six experts in a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, this rate is highest in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the report's authors come to conclusions that run counter to the federal government's position, which has already said it does not want to change the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who also reviewed all the countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuses in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signer of the report, said by teleconference yesterday, there would be more cases of these overflows precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
“Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.”
“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” Downie said.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Eighty-five percent of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia because they believe it would allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid poll.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are of less value.
As for those who practiced assisted suicide, 41 percent said they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing care with a patient, the situation is less clear, the report’s authors say.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The expert committee also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect a denial of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
On palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to deliver better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Finally, with respect to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee calls for it to be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, as euthanasia, and for it to be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some health law experts have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts signatories of the report "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to terminally ill patients.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who would be tired of life and who would be over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Ms. Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
"In society," he said, "there are beacons and constraints."
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she called a "pro-euthanasia manifesto."
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, specifically challenges the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, namely the Netherlands and Oregon.
Jordan's King Calls on President Assad to Leave Power
Damascus denounces "conspiracy"
Syria is increasingly isolated.
Supporters of Bashar al-Assad demonstrated yesterday outside the premises of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
Diplomatic pressure intensified yesterday on Syria of Bashar al-Assad, who, with the support of Russia, resists them and denounces a "conspiracy" against the country.
Two days after Syria was suspended by the Arab League, the European Union stepped up its sanctions against Damascus while Turkey and Jordan, Syria’s neighbors, took a stand in favor of President Assad’s departure.
Jordan's King Abdullah II was the first Arab leader to call on President Bashar al-Assad to "leave power" in Syria, where some 40 civilians and members of the regime's forces were still killed.
"If Bashar was concerned about his country's interests, he should resign, but he should also create the conditions for a new phase of Syrian political life," the king of Jordan, Syria's neighbor, said in an interview with the BBC.
Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoglu said Turkish mediation efforts since the beginning of the year with the Syrian regime had failed.
“Those who are not at peace in the Middle East with their peoples and cannot satisfy them will leave,” he said, referring to Syria, a neighboring country to which Turkey is taking an increasingly tough line.
The United States, for its part, welcomed a "strengthening of the consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime", following the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
"The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League, countries like Turkey are adopting an increasingly harsh tone" in the face of repression in Syria, said Mark Toner, a spokesman for the State Department.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime's forces have died in the southern Syrian region of Deraa, the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH) said.
Two other civilians were killed "during exchanges of fire and shelling with heavy machine guns in Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
At a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Muallem said the country was "stepping towards the end of the crisis".
He also reacted strongly to the decision of the Arab League to suspend Damascus from its work, which he said was "a dangerous step".
Syria “will not bend,” he added, assuring that “the plots plotted against Syria will fail.”
After its decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now considering a "mechanism for the protection of civilians" and wants to send 500 members of Arab human rights organizations, media and military observers to the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé has also said he is in favour of sending UN observers to help protect civilians from the regime's repression, which he says is locked into "paranoia".
A new extraordinary meeting of the League is scheduled tomorrow in Rabat to take stock of the implementation of the crisis exit plan decided on November 2, including the withdrawal of the armed forces from the cities plagued by the protests and the release of the detained protesters.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov said the Arab League's decision was "incorrect", while China urged Syria to implement the exit plan, while being wary of supporting possible sanctions against Damascus.
