Monti demands time from markets and sacrifices from Italians
The future head of the Italian government, Mario Monti, has demanded some time from the markets to train his team and implement a program, which will contain "sacrifices", to recover the credibility lost in the last months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner was in talks with political parties yesterday before meeting with trade unions and employers today.
It should set up a relatively small cabinet of technocrats outside Parliament.
"Monti spoke of an important program with a lot of sacrifices," said Francesco Nucara, a member of one of the many small parliamentary groups involved in the talks, after meeting with the designated council president.
The president of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, for his part, said he expects Mario Monti to request a vote of confidence in Parliament by Friday to ensure that the new government has sufficient support.
