His appointment by the president had initially been hailed by the markets, but worries picked up especially after an unexpected fall in industrial production in the euro zone in September.
The Prime Minister-designate should form a team consisting mainly of technocrats, although he stressed that he would like to include "politics".
The new government is expected to last until 2013, the date of the next legislative elections, he said.
According to the president of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, the new government will gain the confidence of Parliament by Friday.
Mr Monti pledged, once he took office, to work urgently and with the aim that Italy "become the protagonist again" in Europe.
