Russian Scientist Helped Iran's Nuclear Program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, helped Iran develop a detonator that could be used with a nuclear weapon, a U.S. nuclear risk NGO said on Monday.
The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) relies on the recent report of the International Atomic Security Agency (IAEA) and other documents emanating from this UN agency to identify this researcher.
The IAEA said last week it was "seriously concerned" about a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear program.
According to ISIS drawing heavily on IAEA documents, Danilenko, born in 1934, reportedly worked for three decades starting in the 1960s at a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk, Urals, and was involved in manufacturing synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he reportedly left the center to establish a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
The economic difficulties of his company led him to contact the Iranian embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He then reportedly cooperated with the Iranian program from 1996 to 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA cites "strong indications that Iran's development" of a nuclear detonation system "was aided by the work of a foreign expert, who not only knew the technique well, but who, as one member state informed the Agency, worked for most of his career on this technology within his country's nuclear military program."
Anti-Muslim Crimes and Offences Increased by 50%
Crimes and offences against Muslims rose by nearly 50 percent from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, other racial and religious violence fell slightly or made little progress, according to FBI statistics released Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence perpetrated against Muslims increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, representing a 49 per cent increase, compared with a 13 per cent increase in violence against Catholics, a 4 per cent decrease in crimes against Jews and an overall 14 per cent increase in anti-religious crimes and offences.
The total number of “hate crimes” rose very slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3% were motivated by race differences and 20% by religion differences, according to the FBI.
“After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offenses increase again,” Human Rights First said, adding that “the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant.”
“Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be considered a serious violation of human rights,” said Paul Legendre, the group’s chief executive.
“The U.S. government can and must do more to address these abuses,” he said, adding that this could require improved police reporting of “hate crimes.”
The “hate crime” in U.S. federal law is a legacy of the era of civil rights struggle.
This legislation had been passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, skin color, religion, origin and now sexual belonging.
