Austrian
Inclusion of a budgetary "golden rule" in the constitution
The ruling Social Democratic/Christian Democrat coalition government in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a fiscal "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by the rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
The decision was announced by the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann at the end of a cabinet meeting, when Austria's public debt is 74.6%, well above the maximum 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were lowered by just one notch, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an extra three billion euros in interest each year,” said Christian Democrat Deputy Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is following a request from the summit in Brussels of the member countries of the euro area on October 26: the heads of state and government had then demanded the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The system adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural public deficit will have to decrease each year by 0.75% of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring the public debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
Yen fort
Noda threatens further intervention in the foreign exchange market
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would intervene again in the foreign exchange market if the yen continued to rise.
"We will intervene as we did last time if we see excessive volatility" in the yen's exchange rate, Noda told the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen rose not far from historical levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31.
On that day, Tokyo massively sold yen for dollars in order to lower the value of the Japanese currency that had just set a new record for strength since 1945 against the greenback.
But the yen has steadily risen since then, boosted by purchases by investors who consider it a "refuge value" in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar rose below 77 yen on Tuesday and the euro fell below the symbolic 105 yen mark, close to the levels that triggered the last intervention.
Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This surge of the Japanese currency hurts the exports of the archipelago because it increases the cost of Made in Japan products and reduces the value of income from abroad by Japanese firms, when they convert them into national currency.
"Japan is struggling to rebuild" since the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region (northeast), Noda said, fearing that the rise in the yen would kill the fragile recovery.
The world’s third-largest economy returned to growth in the third quarter – 1.5% compared to the previous quarter – for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and household consumption.
But the prime minister said the price of the yen did not reflect "Japan's economic fundamentals".
Finance Minister Jun Azumi called on the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
But the institution's deputy governor, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken "the appropriate measures", suggesting that no further monetary easing was to be expected Wednesday.
At its last meeting at the end of October, the issuing institution increased its purchases of Treasury bills by 5 trillion yen (47 billion euros), raising to 55 trillion yen (519 billion euros) the ceiling of the amounts it devotes to the purchases of various financial securities to flood the market with liquidity.
