Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is a subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy for an election to be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear power in them.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources to continue producing electricity permanently, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation of power plants.
Conversely, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its park by resuming the construction of a plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all of these unpleasant effects are already felt.
The case of Denmark is to be considered.
European champion of wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; according to which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power illusory.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not manifest a principled opposition to this energy, the polls show.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has helped to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it drives a galaxy of specialized SMEs on international markets and makes them very creative of non-relocationable jobs.
If France decides to quit nuclear power, it would be sacrificing many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros of annual French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years when its manufacturer’s decline would be scheduled?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miraculous electricity production, nor is there any diabolical one.
Areva’s development of low-CO2 solutions, both nuclear and renewable, demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as on the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions, with no human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human errors caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the security authorities, French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it able to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians eager to build a power plant, the stopping of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift given to Areva and EDF competitors, leaving them the way to seize leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of numbers, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, with the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic perspective.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left as well as on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confines himself to trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve our “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps electorally paying; but it is very costly economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of country migration flows on employment and wage growth.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and detrimental to employment.
The fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to replace domestic workers, especially the low-skilled, by putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, practicing mainly trades in sectors with a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will struggle to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on nationals' wages and employment.
Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages over the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to the public budgets on average over the course of his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to go and find the missing growth points "with his teeth".
The teeth in question, by serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, European democracy is still to be thought of
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be enough for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct manner possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis of the Europe we are living in is an economic crisis, but it is also, and above all, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have had in this regard the value of a double revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of the political, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought out in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer firing in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to the needs and in a dispersed order.
A white seat to the absolute European monarch or a jump on foot together in the vacuum of nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cutters but an exercise, common, of full right, serene and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal - one would no longer know where to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that is succumbing to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
Europe as a whole is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the steering of the European project.
Because together, Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After a long fight against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for a European economic government.
Oh, yeah.
But to think without a stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take a new step in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe, a true European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
