A rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram – which in Hausa means “Western education is a sin” – advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for sharia law while its militants engage in the struggle against the ungodly central government.
The latter are aimed primarily at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active, multiplying attacks on police stations.
The reaction of Abuja is, as usual, without nuances.
The army invades the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, detained alive, is killed in prison.
From then on the sect will radicalize and leave its northern strongholds.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacked the secure police headquarters in a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the United Nations local headquarters will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia via Nigeria is now a concern for all security experts.
