The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, linking Western Europe directly to Russia via the Baltic Sea floor, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the banks of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe via a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland, in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a rift between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically,” François Fillon confirmed when inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“Around 100 had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project leaders gave it up as the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company settle permanently off their coasts.
"In the event of a breakdown, we stop the gas flow in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have predicted the welds to have a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is provided by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, he delivers accurate information about possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at departure, and 100 bars at arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Germany's E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies set up a joint venture, named Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, the entire gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," Müller said.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was ensured at 30% by the shareholders and at 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure to come back at their own expense, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit gate of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificity of the incoming gas, before it is transferred into German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventure, of hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a off-white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which designates a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has brought back to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, has almost 100 today and since 2008 has two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the trend of the time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diary, pens, computer cases... The brand is available on a range of supports.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy put in place in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, general manager of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, the obstacles remain many before accessing employment.
They are quite old: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, these are criteria that make returning to employment particularly difficult, and that "are the node of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
That's for the objective brakes.
There remains the unsaid, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from meeting the employment target of 6% of disabled workers set in a law of 1987.
The latest known figures, which date from 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, general manager of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, passing from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ workers with disabilities, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
